Just received our team’s SystemCore alpha testing unit, and I love electronics teardowns so I had to take a look inside and share pictures for everyone here.

First of all, roboRIO for scale. image 1920×1440 184 KB

image 1920×1440 184 KB

image 1920×1440 184 KB

Close-up of the front of the device. The front enclosure is 3D-printed (obviously temporary for these early devices). I believe it is printed out of some form of nylon via SLS or MJF printing. Someone more familiar can correct me on that. image 1920×1440 223 KB image 1920×1440 313 KB

image 1920×1440 223 KB

Rear of the device showing the M.2 slot for the Hailo accelerator, currently also 3D printed, but this looks to be FDM. image 1920×1440 137 KB image 1920×1440 144 KB

The rear of the enclosure is anodized aluminum, same as Limelight 3G/A and 4. It acts as a heatsink for the compute module SoC and Hailo module. image 1920×1440 119 KB

Inside of the device. The PCB is covered with a conformal coating to protect against debris. The compute module is the 4GB RAM configuration. image 1920×1440 242 KB

posts.name: Matthew K
posts.cooked:
wow! I love this!

Looks to have an individual CAN transciever chip for each CANbus, as I thought earlier. I’ll take a closer look and come back with my thoughts soon

Overall it looks great I am super excited for this.

My only question based on this design is how they manage the heat. The RPi 5 lacks heatsinking and I know from experience they can get pretty hot running vision detection pipelines in closed cases.

I am interested to hear about the temps from alpha teams and whether they underclock the Pis to manage heat or something along those lines.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked:
TyJac42:

My only question based on this design is how they manage the heat. The RPi 5 lacks heatsinking and I know from experience they can get pretty hot running vision detection pipelines in closed cases.

As shown, the entire bottom case is anodized aluminum that is thermally coupled to the lid of the CM5 SoC.  So it’s a big passive heatsink.
Oh, oops. I just glazed over that. I assumed it was all nylon from the first picture. That should serve as a decent heatsink.

posts.name: billbo911
posts.cooked: Maybe I missed it when the specs were posted, but I’m curious as all get out why there is a WIFi/BT antenna connected via u.fl connector on the CM5?

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: SystemCore includes WiFi, as FTC will need it. FTC doesn’t use an external radio.
